#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Create a development environment with VirtualBox"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:6
msgid ""
"This documentation page aims at explaining how to setup a YunoHost virtual "
"server, using VirtualBox, to work on application packaging."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:7
#, no-wrap
msgid "Why use VirtualBox rather than an actual YunoHost production server to package an application?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:10
msgid ""
"There are mostly two reasons why one should prefer a virtual server rather "
"than their own server:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:13
msgid ""
"You can freely torture a virtual server without any risk of breaking it, "
"since you can always restore it to a former working state. It would really "
"be a pity to break your own real server!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:13
msgid ""
"In a typical workflow, a virtual server state would be restored from a known "
"snapshot before starting any work on it, so as to always keep a clean "
"system, without any residues of a former installation. This allows to always "
"be as close a possible to a user first installation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:15
msgid ""
"We will discuss VirtualBox in this guide, as it comes with an easy to use "
"GUI. If you prefer a pure commandline approach to handling your virtual "
"machine, you should use [ynh-dev](/dev/core/) instead."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:16
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing VirtualBox"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:20
msgid ""
"From a GNU/Linux system, simply install the `virtualbox-qt` package.  From a "
"Windows or macOS machine, you'd have to refer to the [VirtualBox download "
"page](https://www.virtualbox.org/wiki/Downloads) to fetch the appropriate "
"installation package. The virtualbox package is deprecated since Debian 9, a "
"`.deb` installation package is available on the abovementioned referenced "
"page."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:22
msgid ""
"Whatever your system, there should be no need to install the extension pack "
"or the guest addons."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:23
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing YunoHost on VirtualBox"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:26
msgid ""
"Simply follow the appropriate documentation for [installing on VirtualBox](/"
"dev/packaging/misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox) then the [post-installation](/"
"category/after-installation) guide."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:29
msgid ""
"During post-install, there is no need to use an actual domain name in "
"`.nohost.me` or `.noho.st`, as your virtual server won't be reachable from "
"outside your local network.  We prefer using a fake domain name which will "
"remain associated with your local network, for instance `yunohost.packaging`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:31
msgid ""
"This domain name, not being registered with any DNS server, will be stored "
"in the `hosts` file of the computer which will need to access it. Please "
"refer to the documentation about [using a local DNS](/admin/tutorials/"
"domains/dns_local_network) for more information."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:33
msgid ""
"Your virtual server is now installed. Before starting to use it, we'll see "
"how to create a first snapshot and how to use that feature."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:34
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using snapshots"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:38
msgid ""
"VirtualBox becomes even more interesting with its snapshotting feature, "
"which allow to store the virtualized machine state and restore it quickly.  "
"We'll also see how to use multiple snapshot branches to work on different "
"apps on the same machine."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:39
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now, let's create a first snapshot"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:43
msgid ""
"Before starting to play with the virtual machine, now is a good time to take "
"a first snapshot, so that we don't have to redo the full install process "
"every time.  First, stop the virtual machine."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:46
msgid ""
"Managing snapshots is done in the 'Snapshots' tab ![](/img/softwares/"
"virtualbox_packaging1-en.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:49
msgid ""
"Here, we're creating a first snapshot ![](/img/softwares/"
"virtualbox_packaging2-en.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:51
msgid ""
"We can now start to work on the virtual machine and create as many snapshots "
"as desired for each milestone of our modifications."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:53
msgid "![](/img/softwares/virtualbox_packaging3-en.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:57
msgid ""
"In this example, after having validated our particular package removal works "
"fine, we can easily get back in time by restoring the virtual machine to its "
"previous state with the package still installed.  Once the package will be "
"fully functional, it will just be a matter of deleting the snaphots "
"associated with this package work to get the virtual machine back to its "
"initial state.  For our next test, we will then be back to a freshly "
"installed YunoHost serveur, without any trace of package installation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:58
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using multiple snapshot branches"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:61
msgid ""
"In addition to successive snapshots, it is also possible to create a new "
"machine state and additional snapshots from an older machine snapshot/state."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:63
msgid "![](/img/softwares/virtualbox_packaging4-en.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:68
msgid ""
"In this example, I have created two branches since my successful package "
"installation, so as to independently test just the application removal, "
"upgrade and backup/restore steps.  I eventually got back to the virtual "
"machine base state to start a new test on another package, without dropping "
"my former test whatsoever.  At any time, it is possible to get back to a "
"previous snapshot simply by restoring it.  The machine always start on the "
"\"Current state\" state."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:70
msgid "![](/img/softwares/virtualbox_packaging5-en.png)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:72
#, no-wrap
msgid "> It is always possible to create a new snapshot, whether the machine is stopped or not. To restore a snapshot however, the machine cannot be running.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:73
#, no-wrap
msgid "How do we connect to the virtual machine?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:76
msgid ""
"Virtual machine connection is similar to any YunoHost server connection, "
"that is by using SSH."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:77
#, no-wrap
msgid "ssh admin@my.domain\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:82
msgid ""
"Or, if the domain has not been added to the `hosts` file, via its IP address."
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:83
#, no-wrap
msgid "ssh admin@11.22.33.44\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:88
msgid "We can now work on the virtual machine using the commandline."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:90
msgid ""
"To easily copy the package files or use a graphical text editor, one can "
"also connect via SFTP using a file explorer."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:93
msgid ""
"It's a simple matter of using the `sftp://admin@my.domain/` address.  ![](/"
"img/softwares/virtualbox_packaging6.jpg)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/dev/50.packaging/80.misc/packaging_apps_virtualbox.mdx:94
#, no-wrap
msgid "> Note: on Windows or macOS, the file explorer does not natively support the SFTP protocol...\n"
msgstr ""
